Question 1¶

In this question, we are asked calculate average welfare participation (AFDC) by year and plot it. In particular, we are asked to comment on the pre- and post-1996 trends in the data. In 1996, as discussed in class, there were substantial reforms to welfare programmes in the United States.

As an example, we are provided with code to calculate and plot the average hours worked over time. I reproduce said code below to ensure that everything is working correctly, and then plot AFDC as required.

In [ ]:
d = @chain data begin

    groupby(:year) # Grouping the data by year;  each group consists of rows that have the same value in the year column.

    @combine :Hours = mean(skipmissing(:hrs)) # Calculating the mean of the hours worked in each year

    @subset .!isnan.(:Hours) # Subsetting the data to remove any missing values in the Hours column
     
end

@df d plot(:year, :Hours, size = (800,600), label="Average Hours Worked", xlabel="Year", ylabel="Average Hours Worked", title="Average Hours Worked Over Time", legend=:topleft, color=:blue)
In [ ]:
q1 = @chain data begin

    @transform :AFDC_Flag = passmissing(ifelse).(:AFDC, 1, 0) # Create a new column AFDC_Flag 0 or 1 if the ind receives welfare; preserving missing values

    @subset .!ismissing.(:AFDC_Flag) # drop rows with missing values in the AFDC_Flag column

    groupby(:year) # Grouping the data by year

    @combine :AFDC_Fraction = mean(skipmissing(:AFDC_Flag)) # Calculating the fraction of households receiving welfare in each year
    
end

@df q1 plot(:year, :AFDC_Fraction, size = (800,600), label="Fraction of Individuals Receiving Welfare", xlabel="Year", ylabel="Fraction of Individuals Receiving Welfare", title="Fraction of Individuals Receiving Welfare Over Time", legend=:topright, color=:red)

We clearly see that welfare participation fell sharply after 1996, when the Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act (PRWORA) was passed into law in the United States. One of these changes replaced Assistance to Families with Dependent Children (AFDC) with the Temporary Assistance of Needy Families (TANF) programme. Lifetime time limits on benefits were introduced, along with work requirements on participants and individual States were entitled to implement stricter criteria than the federal government in order to qualify for assistance.

In the plot above, we see that the fraction of individuals in our subset of the data who received welfare fell from over 15% to approximately 5% between 1985 and 2008, with the sharpest fall occuring approximately when the PRWORA was passed.

Question 2¶

In this question, we are asked to write code to do the following:

  • Deflate earnings by CPI
  • Calculate average earnings for each individual
  • Drop individuals with fewer than 10 years of data
  • Categorise individuals by whether their average earnings is below or above the median across individuals.
  • Plot average participation in each year for individuals in each of these two categories.

The following code runs the first four steps. That is, it adjusts earnings for inflation, calculates how many years each individual appears in the data and then calculates their mean earnings over the years in which they appear in the data, selects those who appear in the data for at least 10 years, and then finally calulates median earnings and categorises individuals by whether their mean earnings are above or below the median.

In [ ]:
q2 = @chain data begin
    
    @transform :earn = :earn ./ :CPIU # Adjusting earnings for inflation
 
    #groupby([:MID, :year]) # MID identifies individuals

    groupby(:MID) # MID identifies individuals

    @combine :T = sum(.!ismissing.(:earn)) :earn = mean(skipmissing(:earn))
    # Creates a new column T which sums the 0s and 1s from the .!ismissing.(earn) command (0 if missing, 1 if not missing
    # then calculates the mean of the earnings for each individual (skipping missing values)
    @subset :T .>= 10 # Subsetting the data to include only individuals with at least 10 non-missing earnings observations
    
end

median_earnings = median(q2.earn) # Calculate median earnings

# Create a new column which categorises individuals as above or below the median earnings

In order to complete the fifth step, we need to innerjoin the above dataset with our initial dataset (that is, keep the individuals who appear in both datasets) so that we can find the fraction of above and below median individuals receiving welfare over time. We repeat the analysis from question 1, only this time subsetting the data according the the true or false flag we created on median earnings.

In [ ]:
merged_data = innerjoin(data, q2, on=:MID, makeunique=true) # Merge the original data with the initial data

high_merged_data = @chain merged_data begin

    @transform :AFDC_Flag = passmissing(ifelse).(:AFDC, 1, 0) # Create a new column AFDC_Flag 0 or 1 if the ind receives welfare; preserving missing values

    @subset(.!ismissing.(:AFDC_Flag) .& :Earnings_Category .== true) # drop rows with missing values in the AFDC_Flag column and subset to include only individuals with above median earnings
    
    groupby(:year)

    @combine :AFDC_Fraction = mean(skipmissing(:AFDC_Flag)) # Calculating the fraction of above median individuals receiving welfare in each year

end

@df high_merged_data plot(:year, :AFDC_Fraction, size = (800, 600), label="Fraction of Above Median Individuals Receiving Welfare", xlabel="Year", ylabel="Fraction of Above Median Individuals Receiving Welfare", title="Fraction of Above Median Individuals Receiving Welfare Over Time", legend=:topright, color=:green)
In [ ]:
low_merged_data = @chain merged_data begin

    @transform :AFDC_Flag = passmissing(ifelse).(:AFDC, 1, 0)

    @subset(.!ismissing.(:AFDC_Flag) .& :Earnings_Category .== false) # drop rows with missing values in the AFDC_Flag column and subset to include only individuals with below median earnings
    
    groupby(:year)

    @combine :AFDC_Fraction = mean(skipmissing(:AFDC_Flag))

end

low_merged_data = filter(row -> isfinite(row.AFDC_Fraction), low_merged_data)

@df low_merged_data plot(:year, :AFDC_Fraction, size = (800, 600), label="Fraction of Below Median Individuals Receiving Welfare", xlabel="Year", ylabel="Fraction of Below Median Individuals Receiving Welfare", title="Fraction of Below Median Individuals Receiving Welfare Over Time", legend=:topright, color=:green)

A few comments are in order on the above plots.

  • Firstly, we notice that welfare participation is higher amongst below median individuals in all years, but the gap between the above and below median years declines over time.
  • Secondly, looking at the plot for above median individuals, we see that most of the decline in participation seems to have occured before 1996, rather than afterwards. The trend in above median individuals is a steady decrease over time rather than any drastic jumps in or after 1996.
  • This is not true for below median individuals. Pre-1996, welfare participation was steady at around 30%. Participation approximately halfs to around 15% within only a couple of years of the change, and decline to under 10% by 2008.

Question 3¶

In this question, we are asked to use the Transfers.jl file to create a graph that represents total net transfers for a single mother with two kids in the years 1990 and 2000 in the states of Mississippi and New York.

First, let us include the relevant file and run the example from the Assignment webpage.

In [ ]:
include("C:\\Users\\bayle\\Documents\\Github\\micro_labour\\Transfers.jl")
Transfers.budget(500.,0.,23,2000,2,1.,2) ## Example: 
                                         ## a household with 500 in labour income, 
                                         ## 0 in non-labour income, 
                                         ## living in Michigan (SOI code 23), 
                                         ## in the year 2000, 
                                         ## 2 children, 
                                         ## set cpi to 1 if nominal income, 
                                         ## and p to 0 if no programmes, 1 if food stamps, 2 if food stamps and welfare

978.5408333333334

Everything appears to be in order since we got the same answer as the Assignment 1 webpage. Note that Transfers.budget gives net income, net transfers are the difference between net income and monthly earnings. Let's create a function which will calculate net transfers, and so we need a separate function to do this.

We need to calculate net transfers for those who earn between \$0 and \$1000 a month, live in Mississippi and New York, in the years 1990 and 2000. Since we need to work with Mississippi and New York data, the relevant SOI codes are 25 (Mississippi) and 33 (New York). To do this, note that we discretise the grid of monthly earnings into \$50 intervals.

In [ ]:
function calculate_transfers(range, non_labour_income, state_code, year, num_children, cpi, p)

    transfers = [] # Create an empty array to store the results

    for labour_income in range

        net_transfers = Transfers.budget(labour_income, non_labour_income, state_code, year, num_children, cpi, p) - labour_income # Calculate net transfers

        push!(transfers, net_transfers) # append the result to the array

    end

    return transfers 

end

calculate_transfers (generic function with 1 method)

Now that the function is defined, we calculate the relevant transfers. We then plot the results.

In [ ]:
transfers_2000_mississippi = calculate_transfers(0.:50.:1000., 0., 25, 2000, 2, 1., 2) # Calculate net transfers for Mississippi in 2000
transfers_2000_ny = calculate_transfers(0.:50.:1000., 0., 33, 2000, 2, 1., 2) # Calculate net transfers for New York in 2000
transfers_1990_mississippi = calculate_transfers(0.:50.:1000., 0., 25, 1990, 2, 1., 2) # Calculate net transfers for Mississippi in 1990
transfers_1990_ny = calculate_transfers(0.:50.:1000., 0., 33, 1990, 2, 1., 2) # Calculate net transfers for New York in 1990
plot(0.:50.:1000., transfers_2000_mississippi, label="Mississippi 2000", xlabel="Monthly Labour Income", ylabel="Net Transfers", title="Net Transfers by Monthly Labour Income", legend=:topright, color=:blue)
plot!(0.:50.:1000., transfers_2000_ny, label="New York 2000", color=:red)
plot!(0.:50.:1000., transfers_1990_mississippi, label="Mississippi 1990", color=:green)
plot!(0.:50.:1000., transfers_1990_ny, label="New York 1990", color=:orange)

These results are interesting. Firstly, holding the state and monthly labour income fixed, net transfers are more generous in 2000 than 1990, and net transfers in 2000 decline less with monthly labour income than in 1990. That is, transfers in 2000 are less means-tested than in 1990. At around \$550 a month in New York, there is a sharp decline in transfers in both 1990 and 2000 which does not appear in the Mississippi results. This is evidence of the heterogeneity in welfare criteria across states. Lastly, in both 1990 and 2000 whilst mostly being less generous in an absolute sense, and I assume (but I am happy to be proven wrong about this) that the qualification criteria are more strict in Mississippi than in New York, transfers in Mississippi are less means-tested. That is, transfers decline less with monthly labour income in Mississippi than in New York. To maximise transfers, you would need monthly earnings of \$0 in New York regardless of the year, but in Mississippi it differs by year (\$0 a month in 1990, approx. \$300 a month in 2000) which is likely due to work requirement being implemented in Mississippi. Finally, whilst transfers monotonically decline with monthly labour income in both states in 1990, the same cannot be said in 2000; notice a slight rise in transfers in both states in 2000 at around the \$800 a month mark.
